          "messageID": "msg_ceafac76c001KmQ0dt6tc5Inn5",
          "type": "text",
          "text": "\n\nNow I can clearly see the vulnerability:\n\n**In `rules_fuzzer.cc` (line 44):**\n```cpp\nextern \"C\" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const char *data, size_t size)\n```\n\n**In `elf_fuzzer.cc` and `pe_fuzzer.cc` (lines 67 and 72):**\n```cpp\nextern \"C\" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size)\n```\n\nThe vulnerability is that `rules_fuzzer.cc` uses `const char *data` instead of `const uint8_t *data`. This is the \"incorrect argument type\" mentioned in the description.\n\nThe issue is that when the fuzzer passes binary data (which can include null bytes), the `strncpy` on line 54 combined with treating it as a `char*` string can cause issues. Additionally, on line 55, it null-terminates: `buffer[size] = 0`, but the data is being treated as a string when it should be treated as raw binary.\n\nThe YARA rules fuzzer expects YARA rule syntax as input. Let me understand what kind of input would trigger a crash. The vulnerability stems from:\n1. Binary data being passed but treated as a string\n2. `strncpy` copying data that may contain embedded nulls\n3. The buffer being used as a C-string after copying\n\nLet me create a PoC that exploits this. A good approach would be to create input that:\n1. Contains binary data (not just text)\n2. May cause issues when treated as a string\n\nLet me create the PoC file:",
          "time": {
            "start": 1773468863282,
            "end": 1773468863282
          }
