          "messageID": "msg_ceafbc72a0019iK86iTCzj0WU0",
          "type": "text",
          "text": "\n\nI see an issue - the `$a` string got mangled (shows as just spaces). Let me look more carefully at the vulnerable code to understand what would cause a sanitizer crash. The key vulnerability is:\n\n1. `const char *data` instead of `const uint8_t *data` - this is the type mismatch\n2. `strncpy(buffer, data, size)` followed by `buffer[size] = 0` - this writes a null terminator\n\nThe real issue is that when the fuzzer passes binary data with the `const char*` type, the behavior can differ. Let me think about what would trigger a sanitizer crash...\n\nLooking at the code more carefully:\n- Line 49: `char* buffer = (char*) malloc(size + 1);`\n- Line 54: `strncpy(buffer, data, size);`\n- Line 55: `buffer[size] = 0;`\n\nThe vulnerability is subtle. When `size` is very large (close to SIZE_MAX), `size + 1` could overflow, causing a small allocation but then writing beyond bounds. Also, if `data` contains very long sequences, the strncpy behavior with null bytes could be problematic.\n\nLet me create a more targeted PoC that could trigger a buffer overflow:",
          "time": {
            "start": 1773468911617,
            "end": 1773468911617
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "prt_ceafbf8a3001l33SYT0GFoEU4i",
          "sessionID": "ses_315061479ffeCHrUrKkrSJo5M8",
          "messageID": "msg_ceafbc72a0019iK86iTCzj0WU0",
          "type": "tool",
          "callID": "call_0fd906590c5d4ff39a6c24b9",
          "tool": "bash",
          "state": {
            "status": "completed",
            "input": {
              "command": "python3 -c \"\nimport sys\n\n# The vulnerability: when size is close to SIZE_MAX, size+1 overflows\n# But more practically, the issue is with how binary data is handled\n# as a C string when it should be raw bytes\n\n# Create a large input that could trigger issues with the strncpy + null termination\n# The fuzzer harness expects YARA rules but gets binary data\n\n# Strategy: Create input that looks like valid YARA but has embedded nulls\n# that will cause issues when the string is processed\n\npoc_data = b'rule test { strings: $a = { 00 } condition: $a }'\n# Add lots of data to potentially trigger buffer issues\npoc_data += b'\\\\x00' * 5000  # many null bytes\n\nsys.stdout.buffer.write(poc_data)\n\" > poc && ls -la poc && wc -c poc",
              "description": "Create refined PoC with more data"
