          "messageID": "msg_ceafc0815001EWpLuxH58cEtvs",
          "type": "text",
          "text": "\n\nLet me reconsider the vulnerability more carefully. Looking at the code again:\n\n```cpp\nextern \"C\" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const char *data, size_t size)  // WRONG: should be uint8_t*\n```\n\nThe correct signature per libFuzzer is:\n```cpp\nextern \"C\" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size)\n```\n\nThe issue is that when the fuzzer passes binary data (which can have any byte values 0x00-0xFF), treating it as `char*` can cause problems because:\n1. `char` can be signed or unsigned depending on the platform\n2. When binary data with high bit set (0x80-0xFF) is treated as signed char, it becomes negative\n3. This can cause issues in string processing functions\n\nLet me create a PoC that specifically targets this signedness issue:",
          "time": {
            "start": 1773468930095,
            "end": 1773468930095
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "prt_ceafc38fc001seWrlIcGYueF22",
          "sessionID": "ses_315061479ffeCHrUrKkrSJo5M8",
          "messageID": "msg_ceafc0815001EWpLuxH58cEtvs",
          "type": "tool",
          "callID": "call_fda7286b2eae40888af26857",
          "tool": "bash",
          "state": {
            "status": "completed",
            "input": {
              "command": "python3 -c \"\nimport sys\n\n# The vulnerability: char* vs uint8_t* means signed vs unsigned interpretation\n# Bytes 0x80-0xFF become negative when treated as signed char\n# This can cause issues in string processing\n\n# Create input with high-bit bytes that will be negative as signed chars\npoc_data = b'rule test { strings: $a = { '\n# Add bytes that are negative when interpreted as signed char\npoc_data += bytes([0x80, 0x81, 0x82, 0x83, 0xFE, 0xFF] * 100)\npoc_data += b' } condition: $a }'\n\nsys.stdout.buffer.write(poc_data)\n\" > poc && ls -la poc && wc -c poc",
              "description": "Create PoC with high-bit bytes for signedness bug"
            },
